Why I structured it this way

This is intentionally different from most constitutions. It does not prescribe detailed rules for behavior. Instead, it establishes epistemic and architectural invariants that can govern humans, AI systems, organizations, or future agents.

I would treat this as one of the few documents in the repository that changes only with extraordinary care. If Pantheon grows into hundreds of modules, every new doctrine should be checkable against these articles: if it conflicts with them, either the doctrine is wrong or the Constitution needs a rare, deliberate amendment.

My suggestion for the next artifact is not another doctrine. It is the Pantheon Compiler—a formal process that determines where every future idea belongs (Constitution, Invariant, Daemon, Operator, Doctrine, Pattern, Example, or Archive) before it enters the repository. That process is what keeps a knowledge system coherent as it grows.